üî• Python platform Module ‚Äî Full Explanation + Examples

The platform module allows you to fetch system-level information.
It‚Äôs super useful for DevOps engineers, sysadmins, automation scripts, and cross-platform software!

üéØ Key Features of platform module

You can easily get:

‚úÖ OS name (Windows, Linux, Darwin/macOS)
‚úÖ OS version & release
‚úÖ Machine architecture (x86_64, ARM, etc.)
‚úÖ Python version
‚úÖ Node/Hostname
‚úÖ Processor info
‚Ä¶and more!

üìå How to use it?
import platform

üöÄ Common Functions with Examples
1Ô∏è‚É£ platform.system()

Returns the name of the OS.
import platform

print(platform.system())

Output examples:

"Windows"

"Linux"

"Darwin" (for macOS)

2Ô∏è‚É£ platform.release()

Returns OS release version:
print(platform.release())
Possible output:

10 (Windows 10)

6.8.0 (Linux kernel

3Ô∏è‚É£ platform.version()

More detailed OS version string.
print(platform.version())

4Ô∏è‚É£ platform.machine()

Gives architecture:
print(platform.machine())
Possible output:

x86_64

AMD64

arm64

5Ô∏è‚É£ platform.node()

Hostname of the system.
print(platform.node())

6Ô∏è‚É£ platform.processor()

Processor info:
print(platform.processor())

7Ô∏è‚É£ platform.python_version()

Python version:
print(platform.python_version())

8Ô∏è‚É£ platform.platform()

Full OS summary.
print(platform.platform())
Example output:
Windows-10-10.0.19045-SP0
Linux-6.8.0-x86_64-with-glibc2.35

üî• Example: System Info Script
import platform

def system_info():
    print("=== SYSTEM INFORMATION ===")

    print("OS Name:", platform.system())
    print("OS Release:", platform.release())
    print("OS Version:", platform.version())
    print("Machine:", platform.machine())
    print("Processor:", platform.processor())
    print("Hostname:", platform.node())
    print("Python Version:", platform.python_version())
    print("Full Platform Info:", platform.platform())

system_info()

